    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Bulbophyllum kenejiense are tincture, which involves soaking the plant material in a solvent like ethanol to create a concentrated extract, infusion, made by steeping the plant in hot water to release its bioactive compounds, tea, a more diluted form of infusion often consumed as a beverage, decoction, which involves boiling the plant material to release its harder to extract components, and salve, a topical preparation made by mixing the plant extract with a carrier agent like beeswax to create a semi-solid balm for external use. The choice of preparation depends on the desired application and the bioactive compounds present in the plant. Infusions and teas are often used for their antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, while decoctions may be used for their antimicrobial and antifungal effects. Tinctures and salves are often used for their antimicrobial and antifungal properties, as well as their ability to soothe skin irritations. These preparations can be used separately or in combination to achieve the desired therapeutic effect.",
